Locality: Lonoak Road (mp 2 to mp 7 in MTY Co.)

Observation Details: This shrike was hunting from tree to tree along the blue trail between the first two blinds.  I had originally identified this as a Northern Shrike; on 12/6/2022 I received an email from eBird saying that upon their review of my photos it is actually a Loggerhead Shrike which is the much rarer of the expected shrikes we see in the region and to note the wider/thicker mask, light colored chest in the loggerhead vs barred chest in northerns.  Super thanks to Sean Camillieri on behalf of eBird for reaching out to me with this info! :)

Arrivés sur les lieux, ma mère m’indique un oiseau perché sur la clôture. J’ai constaté une pie-grièche, mais étant donné la date et la quantité de noir au masque, je me suis permis de douter sur l’espèce. Nous l’avons observée longuement, elle changeait de temps en temps de perchoir en rasant le sol au vol puis en levant rapidement pour se poser. Très belle surprise, merci à Vincent Giroux pour avoir confirmé que je n’étais pas fou! Photos à venir

Observation Details: First time I've seen one here. It was on the weird treetop next to the old-timey restrooms. Then flew to some small trees just south of the old snack bar or whatever that is. Photographed it for a while as it chowed down on some wasps. Flew toward a flock of finches near the tennis courts and they all scattered. Flew back onto the original treetop and finches near it there didn't seem to mind. Or they were keeping an eye on it, like several Anna's Hummingbirds. Eventually it was chased off of the treetop by an unkindness of 5 or 6 Ravens. Last I saw it was back in those trees just south of the old snack bar.

Grosse trouvaille de Annie Lavoie et de Martin Bélanger ce matin . Ce cimetière est vraiment spécial dans le secteur , un oasis au travers la forêt . L’oiseau est de petite morphologie . Le bec est court . Le masque est épais et très noir . Les marques blanches sur les ailes sont apparentes .  Après 45 minutes d'attente, elle se pointa sur la croix du cimetière vers 19h48 pendant environ 1m30. Lors de l'observation, elle a rejeté une boulette de régurgitation avant de s'envoler dans les arbustes derrière le cimetière où nous l'avons perdu de vue.

Continuing bird. Refound by Russ immediately after all of us failed in refinding the bird and left to sulk at other locations. Perched on lightposts on the north side of the courthouse and would regularly fly into open lot to try and pounce on prey and then return to the light posts.

Continuing on the fence-line west of the first pond. Initially I was leaning toward Northern as the mask isn't especially broad, but I think the bill is short enough for loggerhead and it has a very definite white, contrasting throat.

Unbanded adult. Photos obtained. First spotted by ambiguous birding duo Landon Neumann and Sean Verkamp.  Amy Kearns believes this is a second year bird based on some of the brown seen in the alula, at least based on initial photos of LCD sent via text message.  Bird was seen on power lines at 1200W and 500S initially.  Flew around this area over the course of 20-30 minutes.  We observed it catch and eat several insects on the ground, at least one time flying over at least a portion of GP6E and then shortly thereafter landing in Goose Pond proper just south of 500 for about 10 seconds while it captured an insect.  It ate all of the insects itself and did not seem to be tending to a nest.
interacting heavily with NSHR, but not aggressively.

Lors de l'observation, elle a rejeté une boulette de régurgitation avant de s'envoler dans les arbustes derrière le cimetière où nous l'avons perdu de vue.

It doesn't get much better than this! Only the 2nd confirmed record for Victoria!   Found together with Les Peterson and David Newell atop a Douglas Fir towering over Warbler Woods on the east slope. A moment that we will cherish forever!   We followed the bird up the mountain and relocated it right by the parking lot at the summit. This is where the bird stayed for about half an hour before it flew down the SW slope and was not spotted again.   A touch smaller than Northern Shrike, with broad black face mask, stubby bill, darker grey upperparts and clean whitish underparts. Striking black and white pattern in wings and tail.   My species #350 for the Victoria area (Capital Region). Time to celebrate!

Super thanks to Sean Camillieri on behalf of eBird for reaching out to me with this info! :)

Locality: Fort Funston - for long travelling lists - use specific hotspot where appropriate
Observation Details: Continuing.  See photos. First found 07 March by Keith Maley, these shrikes have been declining over much of their range. This is the only one reported in San Francisco this year. Although classified as a songbird, Shrikes are more predator than anything else. They are famous for impaling their prey on thorns or barbed wire, storing food items for later use. The cause of their continued decline remains elusive. They are currently listed as "near threatened" throughout their range. Note the black mask extends over the top of the bill, helping to distinguish this species from the similar Northern Shrike. Birds in coastal California are presumably "L. l. gambeli" which is small billed, medium gray above with whitish uppertail coverts and gray wash below.

Observation Details: It doesn't get much better than this! Only the 2nd confirmed record for Victoria!   Found together with Les Peterson and David Newell atop a Douglas Fir towering over Warbler Woods on the east slope. A moment that we will cherish forever!   We followed the bird up the mountain and relocated it right by the parking lot at the summit. This is where the bird stayed for about half an hour before it flew down the SW slope and was not spotted again.   A touch smaller than Northern Shrike, with broad black face mask, stubby bill, darker grey upperparts and clean whitish underparts. Striking black and white pattern in wings and tail.   My species #350 for the Victoria area (Capital Region). Time to celebrate!

At the Jct of Peach and Wilkinson, this bird is the most cooperative LOSH I’ve ever encountered. Completely focussed on feeding and seemingly oblivious to my presence. Hawking very small insects (photos) along the roadway….clearly very hungry. It even caught several very close to my feet, and hopped around as if I wasn’t even there. Interesting behavior from a bird that is normally very wary and fleeting.
I believe this was courtship behavior where the male was presenting a potato bug to the female and then changed his mind:-)

Awesome find by Karthik! Thanks for the county bird. :^)  Refound on the west side of Sundial Rd, north of the power station, across the street where Karthik originally reported it. Broader black mask covering the entirety of the eye, stubbier bill, and a thinner, less conspicuous white line above the mask than that of a NSHR. Actively diving into brush attempting to hunt. It wasn't perching too far from the road so standing in one place and giving it space along with a little bit of patience allowed it to perch close to Jill and I for a while. Eventually Andrew refound on the other side of Sundial Rd and Derek joined in.

Continuing great find by Barbara and Adam. Great looks NOT in the rain as it perched for about ten minutes, dropped into the grass, then flew back up to another perch. Super cool bird!

Media notes: Loggerhead Shrike nest located in lower boughs of spruce tree. Nest contains four (4) eggs speckled in brown.
Observation Details: -- RARE and CONTINUING --  Continuing observation of the Loggerhead Shrikes discovered on June 23, 2013. Nest successfully located in a spruce tree between the shoulder of CR-408 and the chain link fence of the airport. The tree is about 15 feet tall with dense branches near the base. Nest is about four (4) feet above the ground near the trunk of the spruce. Nest is well camouflaged and hidden, a bowl-shaped nest with a tight cup in the center and loose material on the exterior, creating a shaggy appearance. Four eggs were observed within the nest, the eggs were small (about one (1) inch in length) and speckled with brown (see photo).  One additional adult Loggerhead was observed, totaling two adult birds. These two individuals are presumably a mated pair, given the presence of a nest. The two adults maintain a presence near the nest, perching on the nearby fence (most often), on the tops of small trees (less often), as well as on snags in the field where they seem to be hunting for prey. While perched the adults exhibit a bobbing tail motion, flicking their tails up and down every few seconds. The field adjacent to the nest site has been plowed and planted, and is quite large in size. Surrounding the field is a forest edge habitat, with mixed hardwoods (primarily beech and maple) along most of its perimeter, with red pine and low scrub around the rest.   When approached, the parent birds emit a grating alarm call while splaying their tail feathers. Often this takes place from the chain-link fence or from atop the spruce tree containing the nest. No other vocalizations have been observed.

This is the site of the reported Northern Shrike.  Although the bird has a number of characteristics associated with Northern Shrike, we identify it as a Loggerhead Shrike.    Evidence supporting Loggerhead Shrike ID: short bill, no scaling on breast.

Cet oiseau effectue de courts vols pour ensuite remonter rapidement pour se percher au sommet de petits arbres et souches présents en bordure de la plage. Photos taken & audio recorded. Confirmation of successful breeding at this site.
Outside the grounds proper, on the way to the parking lot.

Reported to Eastern Loggerhead Shrike Recovery project, public submission withheld at their request until we could determine if this was a breeding bird. Site was surveyed regularly by Mac Forest volunteers over the next few days, but the individual was not relocated, so was likely passing through.

First time I've seen one here. It was on the weird treetop next to the old-timey restrooms. Then flew to some small trees just south of the old snack bar or whatever that is. Photographed it for a while as it chowed down on some wasps. Flew toward a flock of finches near the tennis courts and they all scattered. Flew back onto the original treetop and finches near it there didn't seem to mind. Or they were keeping an eye on it, like several Anna's Hummingbirds. Eventually it was chased off of the treetop by an unkindness of 5 or 6 Ravens. Last I saw it was back in those trees just south of the old snack bar.

Observation Details: Continuing.  See photos. First found 07 March by Keith Maley, these shrikes have been declining over much of their range. This is the only one reported in San Francisco this year. Although classified as a songbird, Shrikes are more predator than anything else. They are famous for impaling their prey on thorns or barbed wire, storing food items for later use. The cause of their continued decline remains elusive. They are currently listed as "near threatened" throughout their range. Note the black mask extends over the top of the bill, helping to distinguish this species from the similar Northern Shrike. Birds in coastal California are presumably "L. l. gambeli" which is small billed, medium gray above with whitish uppertail coverts and gray wash below.

Locality: State Highway 664, Bowling Green, Florida, US (27.635, -81.859)

Observation Details: I was fortunate to have a second shot at this  bird! Great relocation by Caitlin Ambrose 8 days after first found by Jerry. We watched lots of hunting, highlighted by the capture of a dragonfly and subsequent rapid dispatching of the head. I believe it took the dragonfly off to cache, as this was the only time it left the wire and flew deep into the shrubs. It also hacked up a pellet then preened. It occasionally crossed the road at bumper height, or landed on this busy road to pick up small insects. NOTE: We stood on the south side of the road in one spot. The shrike worked a section covering 4-6 utility poles, flying up the road then feeding his way back down the road. With patience it comes close for decent photos. It comes even closer if using the car as a blind.

Locality: Antelope Island SP--Visitor Center & Loop Rd.

Observation Details: Photos taken with 60 X zoom. Saw four shrikes in evergreen trees--at least three were juveniles--and an adult at the top of a nearby tree at the same time. I saw an adult feed one a grasshopper. Another juvenile was guarding and eating off a vole of some sort. It appeared that the head was mostly gone. About 250 metres further west I found three shrikes no more than 50 metres from the nesting tree--at least one was a juvenile and likely two. Both adults may have been present but I didn't see both at once that I was aware of so I can't say for sure. When I walked back to the east I saw an adult shrike lure two of the juveniles to an even further location about another 50 metres east. That is the furthest I had seen them from the nest.

It doesn't get much better than this! Only the 2nd confirmed record for Victoria!   Found together with Les Peterson and David Newell atop a Douglas Fir towering over Warbler Woods on the east slope. A moment that we will cherish forever!   We followed the bird up the mountain and relocated it right by the parking lot at the summit. This is where the bird stayed for about half an hour before it flew down the SW slope and was not spotted again.   A touch smaller than Northern Shrike, with broad black face mask, stubby bill, darker grey upperparts and clean whitish underparts. Striking black and white pattern in wings and tail.   My species #350 for the Victoria area (Capital Region). Time to celebrate!

Photos  Help for other birds originally posted to Discord.---->More info on the Loggerhead Shrike.  This afternoon was my third visit.  I've always been checking the mid level snags (estimate 12-20 feet high) with a couple sightings on Sunday (90 minutes on site), no sightings this morning (20 minutes on site) ,  and this afternoon a sighting upon arrival.  But this afternoon I then saw the bird drop down and realized it also perches on knee high snags.  Twice I found him knee high between M-18 and the pines on the west side of the road.  It also flew  to the east side of M18 and perched knee high.       ...........  Originally I was thinking the bird was diving into pines when it was out of sight.  Now I'm thinking he might be out in the open down low more than birders were realizing........  The bird does not stay perched in one spot very long.  He moves after a short spell whether I tried to get closer views or not.  ....................Hope this helps other birders.  I'll do a checklist later tonight.

Sometimes you just get lucky. Scott and I almost went to Bayside first, but opted to go here instead since the line to get into the National side was so long yesterday. Scott walked out to the beach while I worked the trailside scrub for passerines. As I approached the end of Shell Rd, just before the turnoff to the blind, I saw a largish songbird perched on top of a dead tree straight ahead. Shrike!  I immediately called Scott and told him to come back, then sent a notification to the rare bird alerts. I snapped a few photos before my camera battery died (so frustrating!), then sat in the sand and watched the bird. As soon as I sat down, it flew closer to me - I think one of the trees closer to the path was its preferred perch, and it was waiting for me to move or leave before returning. Scott came back to see it, and Wayne Klockner was in the area and also got to see it.  The shrike worked the immediate area at the end of Shell Rd for the duration of my stay, changing perches every few minutes. It dropped below treeline level once (onto a fallen tree), otherwise it entirely used the taller dead trees in the area. On one occasion, it flew up 10-15 ft above its perch and almost hovered kestrel-style before dropping back down. I never saw it catch anything, but it occasionally spent a few minutes out of view on the ground, so maybe it nabbed a grasshopper or something. It didn't vocalize. I didn't see any interactions with other birds, though the nearby Red-winged Blackbird and Blue Grosbeak seemed to be monitoring it.  What an awesome bird. No idea why it's here, but my best guess is that it's an early dispersal from the Ontario population heading south. I didn't see any bands so I can't confirm/deny that theory. It showed a bit of plumage wear but otherwise looked like a normal, healthy, sleek adult bird.

Watched it for about half an hour as it didn’t look right for a Northern Shrike.  It flew down from the phone line to the ditch across the road three times and came back with food each time.  It looked chunky with a big mask that went over the bill.  I couldn't see any fine streaking on the breast like Northern Shrikes usually have, although those could be worn off at this time of year.  (I finally looked at the photos tonight--June 2--and asked Melissa Hafting for a second opinion--thanks Mel)
Continuing

Was amazed by this find in the field--perched halfway up a tree by the picnic area alongside Mountain Street, unmistakably a shrike with a chunky appearance, black mask and hooked beak, got a good look at it for about a minute until some yellow warblers chased it off. Assumed northern shrike based on location, but got home and looked at photos--thick black mask, proportionally large head, and clean white breast indicates loggerhead rather than northern shrike! Upon conversation with some other birders, appears that a loggerhead would be more expected this time of year than a northern shrike. What a thrill--please see attached photos.

Media notes: Adult Loggerhead Shrike perched on chain-link fence giving alarm call.
Observation Details: -- RARE and CONTINUING --  Continuing observation of mated Loggerhead shrike adults and four nestling young.   Adult birds were sighted perched atop the chain-link fence near the nest site. A quick inspection of the nest yielded photos of the young. The nestlings are still covered in fuzzy gray feathers, and their eyes are open. A black mask is visible around their eyes and lores. I estimate that the young are about 8-12 days old. The observation of the nest was brisk as the adults nearby were aware of my presence and warned me with grating alarm calls.   -- UPDATE -- As of August, 2013  Observations of the Loggerhead Shrikes were not made for a couple of weeks after this observation on July 25, 2013. When I returned in mid-August, an adult Shrike was present. When approached, it maintained a close association with a short pine tree farther to the east down CR-408 from the nest site. I did not see the young, presumably fledged birds, but I assume that due to the known behavior of parent Loggerhead Shrikes to continue feeding their young for several weeks after fledging, the young were within the tree.  Based on the observation of the nest with eggs on June 27 and the partially grown chicks on July 21-25, I can make a rough estimate that the eggs were laid in late June (25-27). The estimates are based on an incubation period of 15-17 days and a nestling period of 16-21 days. I estimate that the eggs hatched in early to mid-July (11-16). The young probably fledged in late July to early August (Jul. 30-Aug. 6). These approximates coincide with the observation of the eggs, hatched young, and finally, the probable fledglings with the adult observed later in August.  A full report of these Loggerhead Shrikes was submitted to the MBRC on July 23, 2013.

Continuing for second day, found by Jeff Effinger. Location description: seen along Ninetown Road(38.9627729, -75.8952830), predominantly moving between woods line, two brush piles, and fence line here (38.9632792, -75.8950014). Seemingly easy and safe to pull off despite the road being busier than you’d expect. Make sure to approach Ninetown from Cow Barn Road—the other direction is functionally private. Description: Shrike with thick black mask which fully covered the eye, subtle and thin white eyebrow, a white washed underbelly and throat but with some subtle cream colors and barring along the breast. Many pics, very cooperative. Fed extensively across afternoon and store multiple kills on branches. (Note to self: 1353 hanging skink photos)

Amazing experience. Where to even start? First, I’ll start by thanking Jeff Effinger and crew for finding the bird yesterday. I’ll also thank John Hubbell for confirming it was still present today, then Maren and Dan for getting us back on it after it disappeared.   This bird was extremely active and perched stupidly close to us at times. At one point it landed in the road about 20 feet away from some of us. It was probably the most active shrike I’ve ever seen, constantly sallying down to the ground,  and usually being successful in catching something. We watched it devour several large insects. It coughed up a pellet halfway through eating one of the insects. It also tried to impale a giant caterpillar but gave up after ten minutes of struggling and ate it. It regularly flew to the tree closest to us after several hunting attempts rather than flying farther away. It chased a Song Sparrow but didn’t catch it. It had an aggressive encounter with a mockingbird, causing three other mockingbirds that I didn’t know were even there to start giving alarm calls. The grand finale was when it impaled a Five-lined Skink a few minutes before I left.   Also it’s banded? Can’t wait to learn its history. Great to see it in Caroline County after recently coming through old Maryland Birdlife issues from when this species used to be common here before disappearing completely.  Banding update: This bird was captive-bred as part of the Smithsonian's Loggerhead Shrike program in Front Royal, VA. It hatched this year, was sexed as a female, and was released near Newburgh, Ontario in August.

Was amazed by this find in the field--perched halfway up a tree by the picnic area alongside Mountain Street, unmistakably a shrike with a chunky appearance, black mask and hooked beak, got a good look at it for about a minute until some yellow warblers chased it off. Assumed northern shrike based on location, but got home and looked at photos--thick black mask, proportionally large head, and clean white breast indicates loggerhead rather than northern shrike! Upon conversation with some other birders, appears that a loggerhead would be more expected this time of year than a northern shrike. What a thrill--please see attached photos.

Birders can help IDNR track these endangered birds - please report sightings (date, exact location, age of bird and color band combination if possible) to akearns@dnr.in.gov  You can support future loggerhead shrike research by donating to the Indiana Nongame Wildlife Fund. Media notes: Loggerhead Shrike, with leg tag and antenna, Port Weller east pier; Sept5'2021; Lucio Fazio
Observation Details: Continuing. Pictures and videos taken. It is tagged on left leg and has an antenna coming out of it.    On the fence by Solar panel at the end of the pier. Twice it flew across to west side of canal and came back to the east side. BUT, at 9:45 am a young man (not a birder) walked right up to the fence very close to it, the LOSH flew west again, but after 10 minutes I left as it did not come back,

MOBS. Gray body with black in the wings and black mask. Bird was found by an unknown birder/photogragher who showed Old Bird photos and asked what it was, and Old Bird refound the bird at the end of the pier. The bird is banded and has an antenna (gps) as seen in photos. Digiscoped photos. Update Sep 9/21 per Dan Pay who got a partial band number off the leg band:  “Further to the Loggerhead Shrike found in Port Weller... I have been contacted by Eastern Loggerhead Shrike Recovery program out of Wildlife Preservation Canada. They are happy to find out this Shrike is from the program. Raised by the Smithsonian Conservation Institute, this bird was released on August 18th in Carden.  ID by my photos the band number was 1252-22463. The pink on his chest was the left over purple markings used during release. Staff at the program were delighted to find out he was eating good, and doing well with the migration. A story is being drafted now with my photos and soon to be released through the Wildlife Preservation Canada and Smithsonian Conservation Biology Institute as well as others. Hopefully with these efforts we will see more of these guys showing up.”

Congratulations to Matt McConnell for finding this bird.  We, along with several other birders, observed it perched on a fence. It left its perch 2-3 times, dropping down into the grass, presumably to catch insects.  Gray upperparts, white underparts. Thick black bill, slightly hooked. Throat white, mask black, wings black, tail black with white edges.Base of primaries white.  A harsh vocalization was heard when the bird was approached by a Red-winged Blackbird.

Observation Details: First observation at 1507. 1 counted on property. Studied carefully in the field and later from photos. Identified by combination of relatively small hook on bill, black mask clearly extending above the eye, and lack of barring on the breast. Expected species for this time of year, but on the late end of the season and also quite rare on this site. First seen perched on a metal fencepost about 10 m SW of the start point. At 1511, it flew down ca 20 m NW to the gravel road and then flew up to another metal fencepost about 50-75 m south with a grasshopper, which it proceeded to eat. A WEME was on one of the other fenceposts immediately SW of the shrike but took off ca 30 seconds after the shrike landed. At 1519 I saw it capture a second grasshopper, dropping down immediately below where it was perched on the fence. At 1541 it was still in the same area and caught at least 2 more grasshoppers. With one of the captures, I definitely observed it using a barb on the fence to hold the grasshopper while manipulating it with its beak. It was still within 100 m of the start point at the end of the survey, and I observed it capture at least 1 more grasshopper and impale it on a barb before eating it. Detections (number 15-minute intervals in which the species was detected): 5 on property.

Regionally Rare:  An adult looking shrike (though my photos show some lighter toned/sun bleached primaries...so perhaps a subadult?) with all black bill, heavy mask, gray back, black wings , light gray underparts. Perched on barbed wire, fence posts a nearby truck. Caught grasshopper and impaled it on the barbed wire and proceeded to eat it from the barb. It appeared to catch at least one other smaller food item which it quickly consumed. Interacted with the nearby mockingbird, chasing it out of sight and then returned to perch and mocker returned a few minutes later and perched near the shrike. The shrike also passed over a few killdeer on the grass , which were extremely agitated by the shrike's presence. There one brief, and harmless, interaction with a Chipping Sparrow which perch on the fence near (below) the shrike.   Essentially this bird was in view for all but a few minutes while I was present, showing extremely nice ...photographed  Originally found be Peter Gararin earlier in the day

Wonderful to see this species in MA. Found while walking the open area with scattered bushes immediately to the south of the Gay’s Head traffic circle and Aquinnah Cultural Center. The bird was moving all about this area hunting from different shrubs. First seen at around 9:25 AM. It was chased off by a pair of Robins at around 10:20 AM, but may have stuck in the area. Shrike with short stout bill and broad black mask. Photos. The 23rd had SSW winds, strengthening as the day progress to a steady 20mph. The strong winds continued through the night shifting to mostly westerly by midnight. I covered this location well in the previous three days, so likely a recent arrival, at least to this specific location. The photographs are not especially clear, but there appears to be contrast between the tertials (fairly dark black) and some of the primaries (worn and browner). Best seen in the close-up photo of the bird looking away and the close-up profile shot. Pyle’s 1997 Identification Guide to NA Birds notes that Loggerhead Shrikes typically replace some tertials in the pre-formative molt (called first basic in Pyle, 1997). The pre-alternate molt is absent to limited (i.e., no flight feathers). So a contrast like this seems to suggest the bird is a second year (first spring). More than happy to hear other thoughts or opinions on aging.

It was perched all the way across the field at Capstone just in front of the wood lot. Fun to watch a mockingbird come at it and lose! Photos stink, but I think they show the no-neck look, small bill, and the mask tapering, but continuing, over the bill - the mask requires more imagination in the photo, but it was visible through the scope. The rich gray doesn't show up as well - washed out. The pure white belly of this bird was a beacon making it easy to find in spite of the distance.

Observation Details: Photos taken and will be uploaded. Clearly an adult loggerhead/northern shrike. Discussed on "Advanced Birding in Ontario" group and consensus was Loggerhead. Identified as LOSH based on stubby, not strongly hooked bill, wide mask, black line of mask extending over bill, no white markings around eye, shade of grey on back, overall structure. Whitish rump not typical for Loggerhead and could imply the prairie subspecies. Perching on roadside wires and signs and dropping to ground to catch insects (grasshoppers?)

Locality: Florida, Pasco, Anclote, Anclote Gulf Park

Observation Details: When first saw the nest there were three juveniles in it. Three juveniles were in a nearby spruce--about 15 feet away. The parents were feeding only the young in the tree away from the nest. Eventually two of the juveniles came out of the nest but remained in the nesting tree. Photos taken with 60X zoom.

Photos taken with 60 X zoom. Saw four shrikes in evergreen trees--at least three were juveniles--and an adult at the top of a nearby tree at the same time. I saw an adult feed one a grasshopper. Another juvenile was guarding and eating off a vole of some sort. It appeared that the head was mostly gone. About 250 metres further west I found three shrikes no more than 50 metres from the nesting tree--at least one was a juvenile and likely two. Both adults may have been present but I didn't see both at once that I was aware of so I can't say for sure. When I walked back to the east I saw an adult shrike lure two of the juveniles to an even further location about another 50 metres east. That is the furthest I had seen them from the nest.

Continuing bird. Showed up at 10:35. Moved around both brush piles, wood stakes in the field, and treeline behind the brush piles. Stashed several prey items around the property and was a very successful hunter!

Was amazed by this find in the field--perched halfway up a tree by the picnic area alongside Mountain Street, unmistakably a shrike with a chunky appearance, black mask and hooked beak, got a good look at it for about a minute until some yellow warblers chased it off. Assumed northern shrike based on location, but got home and looked at photos--thick black mask, proportionally large head, and clean white breast indicates loggerhead rather than northern shrike! Upon conversation with some other birders, appears that a loggerhead would be more expected this time of year than a northern shrike. What a thrill--please see attached photos.

Amazing find by Peter L. Large headed shrike with short, stubby bill, broad black mask that went over the bill, white patches on the wings. After more than an hour searching, saw a MODO flying from the woodlot being chased by something. That "something" turned out to be the LOSH, who perched on a bare tree on the main path a few meters from where I was standing. Was very vocal for a while, may have an audio recording. Record photos taken.

Observation Details: This shrike was hunting from tree to tree along the blue trail between the first two blinds.  I had originally identified this as a Northern Shrike; on 12/6/2022 I received an email from eBird saying that upon their review of my photos it is actually a Loggerhead Shrike which is the much rarer of the expected shrikes we see in the region and to note the wider/thicker mask, light colored chest in the loggerhead vs barred chest in northerns.  Super thanks to Sean Camillieri on behalf of eBird for reaching out to me with this info! :)

Observation Details: Continuing for second day, found by Jeff Effinger. Location description: seen along Ninetown Road(38.9627729, -75.8952830), predominantly moving between woods line, two brush piles, and fence line here (38.9632792, -75.8950014). Seemingly easy and safe to pull off despite the road being busier than you’d expect. Make sure to approach Ninetown from Cow Barn Road—the other direction is functionally private. Observation Details: First spotted by Luis M a little earlier in the morning. Almost certainly a random one-off visit. Not a whole lot of quality habitat for this species here, and the guess is it was attracted to the bugs unearthed in a small, newly-plowed demo farm plot in an open area next to some small trees. Perhaps the miniature farm-like setting looked familiar to it as well. Unfortunately for the shrike, the feast also attracted many of the local nesting contingent (robins, kingbird, flicker, etc.), which made it clear this visitor was not welcome. Between their constant harassment and the rapidly increasing number of people assembling for a field trip, it soon disappeared. I don't believe it has been seen since.

Observation Details: Continuing.  See photos. First found 07 March by Keith Maley, these shrikes have been declining over much of their range. This is the only one reported in San Francisco this year. Although classified as a songbird, Shrikes are more predator than anything else. They are famous for impaling their prey on thorns or barbed wire, storing food items for later use. The cause of their continued decline remains elusive. They are currently listed as "near threatened" throughout their range. Note the black mask extends over the top of the bill, helping to distinguish this species from the similar Northern Shrike. Birds in coastal California are presumably "L. l. gambeli" which is small billed, medium gray above with whitish uppertail coverts and gray wash below.

bird reported some time ago by Scott Evans.  thick black mask extending over bill. relocated the bird still at the cemetery.  bird initially popped up from near the ground or on the ground, as I was scanning the area from the road.  the low area the bird was in could have some water, it looks like some kind of drainage comes through all the heavy brush on the south and east side of the cemetery but I didn't want to approach to close to see exactly what was there.  the cemetery is surrounded by open mining property and nearby GSSF Dugger would seem like significantly better habitat for a LOSH.  The cemetery is a small square with dense brush along two edges and some medium-sized trees.  I didn't see any barbed wire fence but there is some black locust w/ thorns.  I didn't get close enough to see if there's any prey embedded on the thorns.  the area is such a small patch of habitat that it shouldn't be approached.  there's almost zero traffic close to the cemetery in the winter so the bird could conceivably try to stick out the winter if not disturbed. photo will be added.

Media notes: I believe this is a LOSH rather than an NSHR based upon information in RTP's Field Guide To Western Birds.  Specifically,  this bird's mask seems fairly broad and covers the eye completely, and too, the mask continues over the top of the bill.  Also, the breast appears smooth, unlike the faint barring seen on the breast of NSHR.  And unlike the pale lower mandible seen in NSHR, this bird has the all black bill of a LOSH.

Observation Details: At least five, actually.  Seemed there were single, well-spaced-out, shrikes in all directions from the lake, some near (less than 100 yards) and some fairly distant (as much as a half-mile). Most of these were found by slowly scanning the entire area around the lake by scope.  I haven't seen this many Loggerhead Shrikes--from just one vantage point--in probably several decades.  I recall having at least one, and maybe two, family groups of LOSH at the San Jacinto Wildlife Area (in Lakeview [Riverside Co.], CA), back in the mid-1990s, with a total count easily in the double digits.  That, however, was during a survey of the refuge, which covers several thousand acres. This area around Lewis Lake does include at least one nesting territory, as I saw a family group of shrikes back during mid to late summer.
